[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 255     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     would completely dominate the distance calculation, and no_show_rate
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 256     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     (range: 0.0-0.4) would be effectively invisible to the algorithm.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 257     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 258     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 259     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         df: Raw patient DataFrame from Step 1.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     1. Encode categorical payer type as an ordinal number
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     2. Select the feature columns that carry financial risk signal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     3. Z-score normalize so no single feature dominates distance calculations
[0m[49m[39m  260, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  261, 232[0m:[39m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 262     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         Tuple of:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 263     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         - feature_matrix: numpy array of shape (n_patients, n_features), normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 264     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         - scaler: the fitted StandardScaler (save this for transforming new patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 265     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         - df: the DataFrame with payer_ordinal added (for profiling later)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         feature_matrix: numpy array ready for K-Means (n_patients x n_features)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         scaler: fitted StandardScaler (save this for transforming new patients)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         df: the dataframe with payer_ordinal added (for profiling later)
[0m[49m[39m  266, 236[0m:[39m[49m     """
[0m[49m[39m  267, 237[0m:[39m[49m     # Encode payer type as ordinal. This preserves the financial ordering
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 268     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     # that's central to this use case. A purely one-hot encoding would lose
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 269     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     # the information that commercial > medicare > medicaid > self_pay
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 270     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     # in terms of expected reimbursement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # that matters for this use case. A fancier approach would use
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # one-hot encoding, but ordinal works well when the categories have
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # a natural ordering (which reimbursement rates provide).
[0m[49m[39m  271, 241[0m:[39m[49m     df = df.copy()
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 272     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     df["payer_ordinal"] = df["payer_type"].map(PAYER_ENCODING)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     df["payer_ordinal"] = df["payer_type"].map(PAYER_ENCODING).fillna(1)
[0m[49m[39m  273, 243[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 274     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     # Handle any unmapped payer types (shouldn't happen with clean data,
