[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ) -> tuple[KMeans, np.ndarray, list[dict]]:
[0m[49m[39m  307, 278[0m:[39m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 308     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     Run K-Means clustering for multiple values of k and select the best.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Run K-Means for multiple k values and select the best segmentation.
[0m[49m[39m  309, 280[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 310     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     "Best" here means highest silhouette score, which measures how well-separated
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 311     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     the clusters are. But silhouette score is a starting point, not the final word.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 312     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     The real test is whether your finance team can look at the cluster profiles
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 313     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     and immediately name them. If they can't, the segmentation isn't useful
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 314     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     regardless of what the metrics say.
